osbcIndex.description: The value of this object uniquely identifies the instance entry for this class.

osbcBootDirectory.name: osbcBootDirectory
osbcBootDirectory.description: Path to the system files required for booting the system. Example: 'C:\Windows'

osbcCaption.name: osbcCaption
osbcCaption.description: Short description (one-line string) of the CIM_Setting object. This property is inherited from CIM_Setting.

osbcConfigurationPath.name: osbcConfigurationPath
osbcConfigurationPath.description: Path to the configuration files. This value may be similar to the value in the BootDirectory property.

osbcDescription.name: osbcDescription
osbcDescription.description: Description of the CIM_Setting object. This property is inherited from CIM_Setting.

osbcLastDrive.name: osbcLastDrive
osbcLastDrive.description: Last drive letter to which a physical drive is assigned. Example: 'E:'

osbcName.name: osbcName
osbcName.description: Name of the boot configuration. It is an identifier for the boot configuration.

osbcScratchDirectory.name: osbcScratchDirectory
osbcScratchDirectory.description: Directory where temporary files can reside during boot time.

osbcSettingID.name: osbcSettingID
osbcSettingID.description: Identifier by which the CIM_Setting object is known. This property is inherited from CIM_Setting.

osbcTempDirectory.name: osbcTempDirectory
osbcTempDirectory.description: Directory where temporary files are stored. Example: 'C:\TEMP'

win32ComputerSystemTable.name: win32ComputerSystemTable
win32ComputerSystemTable.description: The Win32_ComputerSystem WMI class represents a computer operating system in a Windows environment.

oscsIndex.name: oscsIndex
oscsIndex.description: The value of this object uniquely identifies the instance entry for this class.

oscsAdminPasswordStatus.name: oscsAdminPasswordStatus
oscsAdminPasswordStatus.description: System hardware security settings for administrator password status.

oscsAutomaticResetBootOption.name: oscsAutomaticResetBootOption
oscsAutomaticResetBootOption.description: Automatic reset boot option is enabled.

oscsAutomaticResetCapability.name: oscsAutomaticResetCapability
oscsAutomaticResetCapability.description: Automatic reset is enabled. This capability is available on Windows XP, Windows 2000, and Windows NT, but not on Windows 98 or Windows 95.

oscsBootOptionOnLimit.name: oscsBootOptionOnLimit
oscsBootOptionOnLimit.description: Boot option limit is ON. Identifies the system action when the ResetLimit value is reached.

oscsBootOptionOnWatchDog.name: oscsBootOptionOnWatchDog
oscsBootOptionOnWatchDog.description: Type of reboot action after the time on the watchdog timer is elapsed.

oscsBootROMSupported.name: oscsBootROMSupported
oscsBootROMSupported.description: Indicates whether or not a boot ROM is supported.

oscsBootupState.name: oscsBootupState
oscsBootupState.description: System is started. Fail-safe boot bypasses the user startup files also called SafeBoot.

oscsCaption.name: oscsCaption
oscsCaption.description: Short description of the object a one-line string. This property is inherited from CIM_ManagedSystemElement.

oscsCreationClassName.name: oscsCreationClassName
oscsCreationClassName.description: Name of the first concrete class in the inheritance chain of an instance. You can use this property with other properties of the class to identify all instances of the class and its subclasses. This property is inherited from CIM_System

oscsCurrentTimeZone.name: oscsCurrentTimeZone
oscsCurrentTimeZone.description: Amount of time the unitary computer system is offset from Universal Time Coordinate (UTC).

oscsDNSHostName.name: oscsDNSHostName
oscsDNSHostName.description: Name of local computer according to the domain name server (DNS). This property is new for Windows Server 2003.

oscsDomain.name: oscsDomain
oscsDomain.description: Name of the domain to which a computer belongs. Note If the computer is not part of a domain, then the name of the workgroup will be returned.

oscsDomainRole.name: oscsDomainRole
oscsDomainRole.description: Role of a computer in an assigned domain workgroup. A domain workgroup is a collection of computers on the same network. For example, a DomainRole property may show that a computer is a member workstation. This property is inherited from CIM_ManagedSystemElement.

oscsEnableDaylightSavingsTime.name: oscsEnableDaylightSavingsTime
oscsEnableDaylightSavingsTime.description: Windows XP, Windows Server 2003: Enables daylight savings time (DST) on a machine. A value of true indicates that the system time changes to an hour ahead or behind when DST starts or ends. A value of false indicates that the system time does not change to an hour ahead or behind when DST starts or ends. A value of NULL indicates that the DST status is unknown on a system.

oscsFrontPanelResetStatus.name: oscsFrontPanelResetStatus
oscsFrontPanelResetStatus.description: The following table identifies the hardware security settings for the reset button on a computer.

oscsInfraredSupported.name: oscsInfraredSupported
oscsInfraredSupported.description: Infrared (IR) port exists on a computer system.

oscsInitialLoadInfo.name: oscsInitialLoadInfo
oscsInitialLoadInfo.description: Data needed to find the initial load device or boot service to request the operating system start up. This property is inherited from CIM_UnitaryComputerSystem.

oscsInstallDate.name: oscsInstallDate
oscsInstallDate.description: Object is installed. An object does not need a value to indicate that it is installed. This property is inherited from CIM_ManagedSystemElement.

oscsKeyboardPasswordStatus.name: oscsKeyboardPasswordStatus
oscsKeyboardPasswordStatus.description: System hardware security settings for Keyboard Password Status.

oscsLastLoadInfo.name: oscsLastLoadInfo
oscsLastLoadInfo.description: Array entry of the InitialLoadInfo property that contains the data to boot the operating system that is loaded. This property is inherited from CIM_UnitaryComputerSystem.

oscsManufacturer.name: oscsManufacturer
oscsManufacturer.description: Name of a computer manufacturer. Example: Adventure Works

oscsModel.name: oscsModel
oscsModel.description: Product name that a manufacturer gives to a computer. This property must have a value.

oscsName.name: oscsName
oscsName.description: Key of a CIM_System instance in an enterprise environment. This property is inherited from CIM_ManagedSystemElement.

oscsNameFormat.name: oscsNameFormat
oscsNameFormat.description: Computer system Name value that is generated automatically. The CIM_ComputerSystem object and its derivatives are top level objects of the Common Information Model (CIM). They provide the scope for several components. Unique CIM_System keys are required, but you can define a heuristic to create the CIM_ComputerSystem name that generates the same name, and is independent from the discovery protocol. This prevents inventory and management problems when the same asset or entity is discovered multiple times, but cannot be resolved to one object. Using a heuristic is recommended but not required. The heuristic is outlined in the CIM V2 Common Model specification, and assumes that the documented rules are used to determine and assign a name. The NameFormat values list defines the order to assign a computer system name. Several rules map to the same value. The CIM_ComputerSystem Name value that is calculated using the heuristic is the key value of the system. However, you can use aliases to assign a different name for CIM_ComputerSystem, which can be more unique to your company. This property is inherited from CIM_System.

oscsNumberOfProcessors.name: oscsNumberOfProcessors
oscsNumberOfProcessors.description: Number of physical processors currently available on a system. This is the number of enabled processors for a system, which does not include the disabled processors. If a computer system has two physical processors each containing two logical processors, then the value of NumberOfProcessors is 2 and NumberOfLogicalProcessors is 4. The processors may be multi-core or they may be hyperthreading processors. For more information, see Remarks. Windows Server 2003, Windows XP, and Windows 2000: Because the NumberOfLogicalProcessors property is not available, NumberOfProcessors indicates the number of logical processors available in the system. In the case of a computer system that has two physical processors each containing two logical processors, the value of NumberOfProcessors is 4.

oscsOEMLogoBitmap.name: oscsOEMLogoBitmap
oscsOEMLogoBitmap.description: List of data for a bitmap that the original equipment manufacturer (OEM) creates.

oscsOEMStringArray.name: oscsOEMStringArray
oscsOEMStringArray.description: List of free form strings that an OEM defines. For example, an OEM defines the part numbers for system reference documents, manufacturer contact information, and so on.

oscsPartOfDomain.name: oscsPartOfDomain
oscsPartOfDomain.description: Windows XP, Windows Server 2003: If true, the computer is part of a domain or workgroup. If the value is NULL, the computer is not a part of a domain or workgroup, or the status is unknown.

oscsPauseAfterReset.name: oscsPauseAfterReset
oscsPauseAfterReset.description: Time delay before a reboot is initiated in milliseconds. It is used after a system power cycle, local or remote system reset, and automatic system reset. A value of -1 (minus one) indicates that the pause value is unknown.

oscsPowerManagementCapabilities.name: oscsPowerManagementCapabilities
oscsPowerManagementCapabilities.description: Specific power capabilities of a logical device. The Enabled value indicates that the power management features are currently enabled, but the exact setting is unknown or the information is unavailable. Power Saving Modes Entered Automatically indicates that a device can change its power state based on usage or other criteria. Power State Settable indicates that the SetPowerState method is supported. Power Cycling Supported indicates that the SetPowerState method can be invoked with the PowerState parameter set to 5; Timed Power On Supported indicates that the SetPowerState method can be invoked with the PowerState parameter set to 5; and Time set to a specific date and time, or interval to power ON. This property is inherited from CIM_UnitaryComputerSystem. Value Meaning 0 Unknown 1 Not Supported 2 Disabled 3 Enabled 4 Power Saving Modes Entered Automatically 5 Power State Settable 6 Power Cycling Supported 7 Timed Power On Supported

oscsPowerManagementSupported.name: oscsPowerManagementSupported
oscsPowerManagementSupported.description: Device can be power-managed, for example, a device can be put into suspend mode, and so on. This property does not indicate that power management features are enabled currently, but it does indicate that the logical device is capable of power management. This property is inherited from CIM_UnitaryComputerSystem.

oscsPowerOnPasswordStatus.name: oscsPowerOnPasswordStatus
oscsPowerOnPasswordStatus.description: System hardware security settings for Power On Password Status.

oscsPowerState.name: oscsPowerState
oscsPowerState.description: Current power state of a computer and its associated operating system. The power saving states have the following values: Value 4 (Unknown) indicates that the system is known to be in a power save mode, but its exact status in this mode is unknown; 2 (Low Power Mode) indicates that the system is in a power save state, but still functioning and may exhibit degraded performance; 3 (Standby) indicates that the system is not functioning, but could be brought to full power quickly; and 7 (Warning) indicates that the computerSystem is in a warning state and a power save mode. This property is inherited from CIM_UnitaryComputerSystem.

oscsPowerSupplyState.name: oscsPowerSupplyState
oscsPowerSupplyState.description: State of the power supply or supplies when last booted.

oscsPrimaryOwnerContact.name: oscsPrimaryOwnerContact
oscsPrimaryOwnerContact.description: Contact information for the primary system owner, for example, phone number, e-mail address, and so on. This property is inherited from CIM_System.

oscsPrimaryOwnerName.name: oscsPrimaryOwnerName
oscsPrimaryOwnerName.description: Name of the primary system owner. This property is inherited from CIM_System.

oscsResetCapability.name: oscsResetCapability
oscsResetCapability.description: If enabled, the value is 4 and the unitary computer system can be reset using the power and reset buttons. If disabled the value is 3, and a reset is not allowed. This property is inherited from CIM_UnitaryComputerSystem.

oscsResetCount.name: oscsResetCount
oscsResetCount.description: Number of automatic resets since the last reset. A value of -1 (minus one) indicates that the count is unknown.

oscsResetLimit.name: oscsResetLimit
oscsResetLimit.description: Number of consecutive times a system reset is attempted. A value of -1 (minus one) indicates that the limit is unknown.

oscsRoles.name: oscsRoles
oscsRoles.description: List that specifies the roles of a system in the information technology environment. This property is inherited from CIM_System.

oscsStatus.name: oscsStatus
oscsStatus.description: Current status of an object. Various operational and non-operational statuses can be defined. Operational statuses include: OK, Degraded, and Pred Fail, which is an element such as a SMART-enabled hard drive that may be functioning properly, but predicts a failure in the near future. Non-operational statuses include: Error, Starting, Stopping, and Service, which can apply during mirror resilvering of a disk, reloading a user permissions list, or other administrative work. Not all status work is online, but the managed element is not OK or in one of the other states. This property is inherited from CIM_ManagedSystemElement.

oscsSupportContactDescription.name: oscsSupportContactDescription
oscsSupportContactDescription.description: List of the support contact information for the Windows operating system.

oscsSystemStartupDelay.name: oscsSystemStartupDelay
oscsSystemStartupDelay.description: Time to delay before starting the Windows operating system in seconds.

oscsSystemStartupOptions.name: oscsSystemStartupOptions
oscsSystemStartupOptions.description: List of the options for starting up the Windows operating system. This property must have a value.

oscsSystemStartupSetting.name: oscsSystemStartupSetting
oscsSystemStartupSetting.description: Index of the default start up profile. This value is calculated so that it usually returns 0 (zero), because at write-time the profile string is physically moved to the top of the list, which is how Windows NT determines the default value.

oscsSystemType.name: oscsSystemType
oscsSystemType.description: System running on the Windows computer. This property must have a value.

oscsThermalState.name: oscsThermalState
oscsThermalState.description: Thermal state of the system when last booted.

oscsTotalPhysicalMemory.name: oscsTotalPhysicalMemory
oscsTotalPhysicalMemory.description: Total size of physical memory. Example: 67108864

oscsUserName.name: oscsUserName
oscsUserName.description: Name of a user that is logged on currently. This property must have a value. In a terminal services session, UserName returns the name of the user that is logged on to the console not the user logged on during the terminal service session. Example: jeffsmith

oscsWakeUpType.name: oscsWakeUpType
oscsWakeUpType.description: Event that causes the system to power up.

oscsWorkgroup.name: oscsWorkgroup
oscsWorkgroup.description: Windows Server 2003 and Windows XP: Name of the workgroup for this computer. If the value of the PartOfDomain property is false, then the name of the workgroup is returned.

oscsAutomaticManagedPagefile.name: oscsAutomaticManagedPagefile
oscsAutomaticManagedPagefile.description: If True, the system manages the page file.

oscsNumberOfLogicalProcessors.name: oscsNumberOfLogicalProcessors
oscsNumberOfLogicalProcessors.description: Number of logical processors available on the computer. You can use NumberOfLogicalProcessors and NumberOfProcessors to determine if the computer is hyperthreading. For more information, see Remarks.

oscsPCSystemType.name: oscsPCSystemType
oscsPCSystemType.description: Type of the computer in use, such as laptop, desktop, or Tablet.

win32ComputerSystemProductTable.name: win32ComputerSystemProductTable
win32ComputerSystemProductTable.description: The Win32_ComputerSystemProduct WMI class represents a product. This includes software and hardware used on this computer system.

oscspIndex.name: oscspIndex
oscspIndex.description: The value of this object uniquely identifies the instance entry for this class.

oscspCaption.name: oscspCaption
oscspCaption.description: Short description of the object a one-line string. This property is inherited from CIM_Product.

oscspDescription.name: oscspDescription
oscspDescription.description: Description of the product. This property is inherited from CIM_Product.

oscspIdentifyingNumber.name: oscspIdentifyingNumber
oscspIdentifyingNumber.description: Product identification such as a serial number on software or a die number on a hardware chip. This property is inherited from CIM_Product.

oscspName.name: oscspName
oscspName.description: Commonly used product name. This property is inherited from CIM_Product.

oscspSKUNumber.name: oscspSKUNumber
oscspSKUNumber.description: Product SKU (stock-keeping unit) information. This property is inherited from CIM_Product.

oscspUUID.name: oscspUUID
oscspUUID.description: Universally unique identifier (UUID) for this product. A UUID is a 128-bit identifier that is guaranteed to be different from other generated UUIDs. If a UUID is not available, a UUID of all zeros is used.

oscspVendor.name: oscspVendor
oscspVendor.description: Name of the product supplier. Corresponds to the Vendor property in the product object in the Desktop Management Task Force (DMTF) Solution Exchange Standard. This property is inherited from CIM_Product.

oscspVersion.name: oscspVersion
oscspVersion.description: Product version information. Corresponds to the Version property in the product object in the DMTF Solution Exchange Standard. This property is inherited from CIM_Product.

win32LoadOrderGroupTable.name: win32LoadOrderGroupTable
win32LoadOrderGroupTable.description: The Win32_LoadOrderGroup WMI class represents a group of system services that define execution dependencies. The services must be initiated in the order specified by the Load Order Group, as the services are dependent on each other. These dependent services require the presence of the antecedent services to function correctly. The data in this class is derived by the provider from the registry key: System\CurrentControlSet\Control\GroupOrderList

oslogIndex.name: oslogIndex
oslogIndex.description: The value of this object uniquely identifies the instance entry for this class.

oslogCaption.name: oslogCaption
oslogCaption.description: Short description (one-line string) of the object.

oslogDriverEnabled.name: oslogDriverEnabled
oslogDriverEnabled.description: Indicates whether this load order group can include drivers along with system services.

oslogGroupOrder.name: oslogGroupOrder
oslogGroupOrder.description: Sequence in which this group of services is loaded onto the operating system. Example: 2

oslogInstallDate.name: oslogInstallDate
oslogInstallDate.description: Date object was installed. This property does not require a value to indicate that the object is installed.

oslogName.name: oslogName
oslogName.description: Name of the load order group. Example: 'Primary disk'

oslogStatus.name: oslogStatus
oslogStatus.description: Current status of the object. Various operational and non-operational statuses can be defined. Operational statuses include: 'OK', 'Degraded', and 'Pred Fail' (an element, such as a SMART-enabled hard drive, may function properly but predicts a failure in the near future). Non-operational statuses include: 'Error', 'Starting', 'Stopping', and 'Service'. The 'Service' status applies to administrative work, such as mirror-resilvering of a disk or reload of a user permissions list. Not all such work is on-line, yet the managed element is neither 'OK' nor in one of the other states.

win32OperatingSystemTable.name: win32OperatingSystemTable
win32OperatingSystemTable.description: The Win32_OperatingSystem WMI class represents an operating system installed on a Windows computer system. Any operating system that can be installed on a Windows system is a descendent or member of this class. If a computer has multiple operating systems installed, this class returns only an instance for the currently active operating system.

ososIndex.name: ososIndex
ososIndex.description: The value of this object uniquely identifies the instance entry for this class.

ososBootDevice.name: ososBootDevice
ososBootDevice.description: Name of the disk drive from which the Windows operating system boots. Example: '\\Device\Harddisk0'

ososBuildNumber.name: ososBuildNumber
ososBuildNumber.description: Build number of an operating system. It can be used for more precise version information than product release version numbers. Example: '1381'

ososBuildType.name: ososBuildType
ososBuildType.description: Type of build used for an operating system. Examples: 'retail build', 'checked build'

ososCaption.name: ososCaption
ososCaption.description: Short description of the object a one-line string. The string includes the operating system version. For example, 'Microsoft Windows XP Professional Version = 5.1.2500'. This property can be localized.

ososCodeSet.name: ososCodeSet
ososCodeSet.description: Code page value an operating system uses. A code page contains a character table that an operating system uses to translate strings for different languages. The American National Standards Institute (ANSI) lists values that represent defined code pages. If an operating system does not use an ANSI code page, this member is set to 0 (zero). The CodeSet string can use up to six characters to define the code page value. Example: '1255'

ososCountryCode.name: ososCountryCode
ososCountryCode.description: Code for the country/region that an operating system uses. Values are based on international phone dialing prefixes also referred to as IBM country/region codes. The property can use up to six characters to define the country/region code value. Example: '1' (United States)

ososCreationClassName.name: ososCreationClassName
ososCreationClassName.description: Name of the first concrete class that appears in the inheritance chain used in the creation of an instance. When used with other key properties of the class, the property allows all instances of this class and its subclasses to be identified uniquely.

ososCSCreationClassName.name: ososCSCreationClassName
ososCSCreationClassName.description: Creation class name of the scoping computer system.

ososCSDVersion.name: ososCSDVersion
ososCSDVersion.description: Null-terminated string that indicates the latest service pack installed on a computer system. If no service pack is installed, the string is NULL. For computers running Windows 95, this property contains a null-terminated string that provides arbitrary additional information about the operating system. Example: 'Service Pack 3'

ososCSName.name: ososCSName
ososCSName.description: Name of the scoping computer system.

ososCurrentTimeZone.name: ososCurrentTimeZone
ososCurrentTimeZone.description: Number of minutes an operating system is offset from Greenwich mean time (GMT). The number is positive, negative, or zero.

ososDataExecPrevention32BitAppl.name: ososDataExecPrevention32BitAppl
ososDataExecPrevention32BitAppl.description: When the data execution prevention hardware feature is available, then if TRUE, this property indicates that the feature is set to work for 32-bit applications. On 64-bit computers, the data execution prevention feature is configured in the Boot.ini file and the properties in Win32_OperatingSystem are set accordingly. This property is set to FALSE on 32-bit computers. Windows XP SP1 and earlier: This property is not available. Windows Server 2003 and earlier: This property is not available.

ososDataExecPreventionAvailable.name: ososDataExecPreventionAvailable
ososDataExecPreventionAvailable.description: Data execution prevention is an AMD 64-bit hardware feature to prevent buffer overrun attacks by stopping the execution of code on data type memory pages. If TRUE, then this feature is available. On 64-bit computers, the data execution prevention feature is configured in the Boot.ini file and the properties in Win32_OperatingSystem are set accordingly. This property is set to FALSE on 32-bit computers. Windows XP SP1 and earlier: This property is not available. Windows Server 2003 and earlier: This property is not available.

ososDataExecPreventionDrivers.name: ososDataExecPreventionDrivers
ososDataExecPreventionDrivers.description: When the data execution prevention hardware feature is available, then if TRUE, this property indicates that the feature is set to work for drivers. On 64-bit computers, the data execution prevention feature is configured in the Boot.ini file and the properties in Win32_OperatingSystem are set accordingly. This property is set to FALSE on 32-bit computers. Windows XP SP1 and earlier: This property is not available. Windows Server 2003 and earlier: This property is not available.

ososDebug.name: ososDebug
ososDebug.description: Operating system is a checked (debug) build. If TRUE, the debugging version of User.exe is installed. Checked builds provide error checking, argument verification, and system debugging code. Additional code in a checked binary generates a kernel debugger error message and breaks into the debugger. This helps immediately determine the cause and location of the error. Performance suffers in a checked build due to the additional code that is executed.

ososDescription.name: ososDescription
ososDescription.description: Description of the Windows operating system. Some user interfaces (those that allow editing of this description) limit its length to 48 characters.

ososDistributed.name: ososDistributed
ososDistributed.description: Operating system is distributed across several computer system nodes. If so, these nodes should be grouped as a cluster.

ososEncryptionLevel.name: ososEncryptionLevel
ososEncryptionLevel.description: Windows Server 2003, Windows XP: Encryption level for secure transactions 40-bit, 128-bit, or n-bit.

ososForegroundApplicationBoost.name: ososForegroundApplicationBoost
ososForegroundApplicationBoost.description: Increase in priority given to the foreground application. On computer systems running Windows NT 4.0 and Windows 2000, application boost is implemented by giving an application more execution time slices (quantum lengths). A ForegroundApplicationBoost value of 0 (zero) indicates the system boosts the quantum length by 6; if 1, then 12; and if 2 then 18. On Windows NT 3.51 and earlier, application boost is implemented by increasing the scheduling priority. For these systems, the scheduling priority is increased by the value of this property. The default value is 2.

ososFreePhysicalMemory.name: ososFreePhysicalMemory
ososFreePhysicalMemory.description: Number of kilobytes of physical memory currently unused and available.

ososFreeSpaceInPagingFiles.name: ososFreeSpaceInPagingFiles
ososFreeSpaceInPagingFiles.description: Number of kilobytes that can be mapped into the operating system paging files without causing any other pages to be swapped out.

ososFreeVirtualMemory.name: ososFreeVirtualMemory
ososFreeVirtualMemory.description: Number of kilobytes of virtual memory currently unused and available. For example, this may be calculated by adding the amount of free RAM to the amount of free paging space, that is, adding the FreePhysicalMemory and FreeSpaceInPagingFiles properties.

ososInstallDate.name: ososInstallDate
ososInstallDate.description: Date object was installed. This property does not require a value to indicate that the object is installed.

ososLargeSystemCache.name: ososLargeSystemCache
ososLargeSystemCache.description: Indicates whether or not to optimize memory for applications or system performance. Windows 2000 and earlier: This property is not available.

ososLocalDateTime.name: ososLocalDateTime
ososLocalDateTime.description: Operating system's version of the local date and time of day.

ososLocale.name: ososLocale
ososLocale.description: Language identifier used by the operating system. A language identifier is a standard international numeric abbreviation for a country/region. Each language has a unique language identifier (LANGID), a 16-bit value that consists of a primary language identifier and a secondary language identifier.

ososManufacturer.name: ososManufacturer
ososManufacturer.description: Name of the operating system manufacturer. For Windows systems, this value is 'Microsoft Corporation'.

ososMaxNumberOfProcesses.name: ososMaxNumberOfProcesses
ososMaxNumberOfProcesses.description: Maximum number of process contexts the operating system can support. If there is no fixed maximum, the value should be 0 (zero). On systems that have a fixed maximum, this object can help diagnose failures that occur when the maximum is reached if unknown, enter -1.

ososMaxProcessMemorySize.name: ososMaxProcessMemorySize
ososMaxProcessMemorySize.description: Maximum number of kilobytes of memory that can be allocated to a process. For operating systems with no virtual memory, typically this value is equal to the total amount of physical memory minus the memory used by the BIOS and OS. For some operating systems, this value may be infinity, in which case 0 (zero) should be entered. In other cases, this value could be a constant, for example, 2G or 4G.

ososName.name: ososName
ososName.description: Operating system instance within a computer system.

ososNumberOfLicensedUsers.name: ososNumberOfLicensedUsers
ososNumberOfLicensedUsers.description: Number of user licenses for the operating system. If unlimited, enter 0 (zero). If unknown, enter -1.

ososNumberOfProcesses.name: ososNumberOfProcesses
ososNumberOfProcesses.description: Number of process contexts currently loaded or running on the operating system.

ososNumberOfUsers.name: ososNumberOfUsers
ososNumberOfUsers.description: Number of user sessions for which the operating system is storing state information currently.

ososOrganization.name: ososOrganization
ososOrganization.description: Company name for the registered user of the operating system. Example: 'Microsoft Corporation'

ososOSLanguage.name: ososOSLanguage
ososOSLanguage.description: Language version of the operating system installed.

ososOSProductSuite.name: ososOSProductSuite
ososOSProductSuite.description: Installed and licensed system product additions to the operating system. For example, the value of 146 (0x92) for OSProductSuite indicates Enterprise, Terminal Server, and Data Center (bits one, four, and seven set). The following table identifies the possible values. Value Meaning 0x1 Small Business 0x2 Enterprise 0x4 BackOffice 0x8 Communication Server 0x10 Terminal Server 0x20 Small Business (Restricted) 0x40 Embedded NT 0x80 Data Center

ososOtherTypeDescription.name: ososOtherTypeDescription
ososOtherTypeDescription.description: Manufacturer and operating system type that is used when the operating system property OSType is set to 1 (Other). The format of the string inserted in OtherTypeDescription should be similar in format to the value strings defined for OSType. The OtherTypeDescription property should be set to NULL when OSType is any value other than 1.

ososPAEEnabled.name: ososPAEEnabled
ososPAEEnabled.description: Physical Address Extension (PAE) is enabled by the operating system running on Intel processors. PAE allows applications to address more than 4 GB of physical memory. When PAE is enabled, the operating system uses three-level linear address translation rather than two-level. Providing more physical memory to an application reduces the need to swap memory to the page file and increases performance. To enable, PAE, use the /PAE switch in the Boot.ini file. Windows XP and earlier: The PAEEnabled property is not available.

ososPlusProductID.name: ososPlusProductID
ososPlusProductID.description: Identification number for the Windows Plus! operating system enhancement software if installed.

ososPlusVersionNumber.name: ososPlusVersionNumber
ososPlusVersionNumber.description: Version number of the Windows Plus! operating system enhancement software if installed.

ososQuantumLength.name: ososQuantumLength
ososQuantumLength.description: Number of clock ticks per quantum. A quantum is a unit of execution time that the scheduler is allowed to give to an application before switching to other applications. When a thread runs one quantum, the kernel preempts it and moves it to the end of a queue for applications with equal priorities. The actual length of a thread's quantum varies across different Windows platforms Windows NT/Windows 2000 only.

ososQuantumType.name: ososQuantumType
ososQuantumType.description: Length type of quantums. Windows NT 4.0 Workstation/Windows 2000 defaults to variable-length quantums where the foreground application has a longer quantum than the background applications. Windows NT server defaults to fixed-length quantums. A quantum is a unit of execution time that the scheduler is allowed to give to an application before switching to another application. When a thread runs one quantum, the kernel preempts it and moves it to the end of a queue for applications with equal priorities. The actual length of a thread's quantum varies across different Windows platforms. For Windows NT/Windows 2000 only.

ososRegisteredUser.name: ososRegisteredUser
ososRegisteredUser.description: Name of the registered user of the operating system. Example: 'Ben Smith'

ososSerialNumber.name: ososSerialNumber
ososSerialNumber.description: Operating system product serial identification number. Example: '10497-OEM-0031416-71674'

ososServicePackMajorVersion.name: ososServicePackMajorVersion
ososServicePackMajorVersion.description: Major version number of the service pack installed on the computer system. If no service pack has been installed, the value is 0 (zero). Windows NT 4.0, Windows Me/98/95: This property is present but the value is NULL.

ososServicePackMinorVersion.name: ososServicePackMinorVersion
ososServicePackMinorVersion.description: Minor version number of the service pack installed on the computer system. If no service pack has been installed, the value is 0 (zero). Windows NT 4.0, Windows Me/98/95: This property is present but the value is NULL.

ososSizeStoredInPagingFiles.name: ososSizeStoredInPagingFiles
ososSizeStoredInPagingFiles.description: Total number of kilobytes that can be stored in the operating system's paging files 0 (zero) indicates that there are no paging files. Note that this number does not represent the actual physical size of the paging file on disk.

ososStatus.name: ososStatus
ososStatus.description: Current status of the object. Various operational and non-operational statuses can be defined. Operational statuses include: 'OK', 'Degraded', and 'Pred Fail' (an element, such as a SMART-enabled hard drive may function properly, but predicts a failure in the near future). Non-operational statuses include: 'Error', 'Starting', 'Stopping', and 'Service'. The 'Service' status applies to administrative work, such as mirror-resilvering of a disk, reload of a user permissions list, or other administrative work. Not all such work is online, but the managed element is neither 'OK' nor in one of the other states.

ososSuiteMask.name: ososSuiteMask
ososSuiteMask.description: Bit flags that identify the product suites available on the system. Windows 2000 Server and earlier, Windows 2000 and earlier: This property is not available. For example, to specify both Personal and Back Office you set SuiteMask to 4 | 512 or 516. The following table identifies the possible values. Value Meaning 1 Small Business 2 Enterprise 4 Back Office 8 Communications 16 Terminal 32 Small Business Restricted 64 Embedded NT 128 Data Center 256 Single User 512 Personal 1024 Blade

ososSystemDevice.name: ososSystemDevice
ososSystemDevice.description: Physical disk partition on which the operating system is installed.

ososSystemDirectory.name: ososSystemDirectory
ososSystemDirectory.description: System directory of the operating system. Example: 'C:\WINDOWS\SYSTEM32'

ososSystemDrive.name: ososSystemDrive
ososSystemDrive.description: Letter of the disk drive on which the operating system resides. Example: 'C:' Windows 2000 Server and earlier, Windows 2000 and earlier: This property is not available.

ososTotalSwapSpaceSize.name: ososTotalSwapSpaceSize
ososTotalSwapSpaceSize.description: Total swap space in kilobytes. This value may be NULL (unspecified) if swap space is not distinguished from page files. However, some operating systems distinguish these concepts. For example, in UNIX, whole processes can be swapped out when the free page list falls and remains below a specified amount.

ososTotalVirtualMemorySize.name: ososTotalVirtualMemorySize
ososTotalVirtualMemorySize.description: Number of kilobytes of virtual memory. For example, this may be calculated by adding the amount of total RAM to the amount of paging space, that is, adding the amount of memory in or aggregated by the computer system to the property, SizeStoredInPagingFiles.

ososTotalVisibleMemorySize.name: ososTotalVisibleMemorySize
ososTotalVisibleMemorySize.description: Total amount of physical memory available to the operating system. This value does not necessarily indicate the true amount of physical memory, but what is reported to the operating system as available to it.

ososVersion.name: ososVersion
ososVersion.description: Version number of the operating system. Example: '4.0'

ososWindowsDirectory.name: ososWindowsDirectory
ososWindowsDirectory.description: Windows directory of the operating system. Example: 'C:\WINDOWS'

win32OSRecoveryConfigTable.name: win32OSRecoveryConfigTable
win32OSRecoveryConfigTable.description: The Win32_OSRecoveryConfiguration WMI class represents the types of information that will be gathered from memory when the operating system fails. This includes boot failures and system crashes.

osrcIndex.name: osrcIndex
osrcIndex.description: The value of this object uniquely identifies the instance entry for this class.

osrcAutoReboot.name: osrcAutoReboot
osrcAutoReboot.description: System will automatically reboot during a recovery operation.

osrcCaption.name: osrcCaption
osrcCaption.description: Short description of the CIM_Setting object a one-line string.

osrcDebugFilePath.name: osrcDebugFilePath
osrcDebugFilePath.description: Full path to the debug file. A debug file is created with the memory state of the computer after a computer failure. Example: 'C:\WinNT\Memory.dmp'

osrcDebugInfoType.name: osrcDebugInfoType
osrcDebugInfoType.description: Windows XP, Windows Server 2003: Type of debugging information written to the log file.

osrcExpandedDebugFilePath.name: osrcExpandedDebugFilePath
osrcExpandedDebugFilePath.description: Windows XP, Windows Server 2003: Expanded version of the DebugFilePath property. Example: 'C:\WinNT\Memory.dmp'

osrcExpandedMiniDumpDirectory.name: osrcExpandedMiniDumpDirectory
osrcExpandedMiniDumpDirectory.description: Windows XP, Windows Server 2003: Expanded version of the MiniDumpDirectory property. Example: 'C:\WinNT\MiniDump'

osrcKernelDumpOnly.name: osrcKernelDumpOnly
osrcKernelDumpOnly.description: Only kernel debug information will be written to the debug log file. If TRUE, then only the state of the kernel is written to a file in the event of a system failure. If FALSE, the system will try to log the state of the memory, and any devices that can provide information about the system when it failed.

osrcMiniDumpDirectory.name: osrcMiniDumpDirectory
osrcMiniDumpDirectory.description: Windows XP, Windows Server 2003: Directory where small memory dump files will be recorded and accumulated. Example: '%systemRoot%\MiniDump'

osrcName.name: osrcName
osrcName.description: Identifying name for this instance of the Win32_OSRecoveryConfiguration class.

osrcOverwriteExistingDebugFile.name: osrcOverwriteExistingDebugFile
osrcOverwriteExistingDebugFile.description: New log file will overwrite an existing one.

osrcSendAdminAlert.name: osrcSendAdminAlert
osrcSendAdminAlert.description: Alert message will be sent to the system administrator in the event of an operating system failure.

osrcSettingID.name: osrcSettingID
osrcSettingID.description: Identifier by which the CIM_Setting object is known.

osrcWriteDebugInfo.name: osrcWriteDebugInfo
osrcWriteDebugInfo.description: Debugging information is to be written to a log file.

osrcWriteToSystemLog.name: osrcWriteToSystemLog
osrcWriteToSystemLog.description: Events will be written to a system log.

win32QuickFixEngineeringTable.name: win32QuickFixEngineeringTable
win32QuickFixEngineeringTable.description: The Win32_QuickFixEngineering WMI class represents system-wide Quick Fix Engineering (QFE) or updates that have been applied to the current operating system.

osqfeIndex.name: osqfeIndex
osqfeIndex.description: The value of this object uniquely identifies the instance entry for this class.

osqfeCaption.name: osqfeCaption
osqfeCaption.description: Short textual description (one-line string) of the object.

osqfeCSName.name: osqfeCSName
osqfeCSName.description: Local name of the computer system. The value for this property comes from the CIM_ComputerSystem class.

osqfeFixComments.name: osqfeFixComments
osqfeFixComments.description: Additional comments relating to the update. This property represents data found in the Windows registry key: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE SOFTWARE Microsoft Windows NT CurrentVersion Hotfix

osqfeHotFixID.name: osqfeHotFixID
osqfeHotFixID.description: Unique identifier associated with a particular QFE. This property represents data found in the Windows registry key: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE SOFTWARE Microsoft Windows NT CurrentVersion Hotfix

osqfeInstallDate.name: osqfeInstallDate
osqfeInstallDate.description: Object was installed. This property does not need a value to indicate that the object is installed.

osqfeInstalledBy.name: osqfeInstalledBy
osqfeInstalledBy.description: Person who installed the update. If this value is unknown, the property will be empty. This property represents data found in the Windows registry key: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE SOFTWARE Microsoft Windows NT CurrentVersion Hotfix

osqfeInstalledOn.name: osqfeInstalledOn
osqfeInstalledOn.description: Update was installed. If this value is unknown, the property will be empty. This property represents data found in the Windows registry key: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE SOFTWARE Microsoft Windows NT CurrentVersion Hotfix

osqfeName.name: osqfeName
osqfeName.description: Label by which the object is known. When subclassed, the property can be overridden to be a key property.

osqfeServicePackInEffect.name: osqfeServicePackInEffect
osqfeServicePackInEffect.description: Service pack in effect when the update was applied. If no service pack has been applied, the property takes on the value SP0. If it cannot be determined what service pack was in effect, this property will be NULL. This property represents data found in the Windows registry key: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE SOFTWARE Microsoft Windows NT CurrentVersion Hotfix

osqfeStatus.name: osqfeStatus
osqfeStatus.description: Current status of the object. Various operational and non-operational statuses can be defined. Operational statuses include: 'OK', 'Degraded', and 'Pred Fail' (an element, such as a SMART-enabled hard drive, may be functioning properly but predicting a failure in the near future). Non-operational statuses include: 'Error', 'Starting', 'Stopping', and 'Service'. The latter, 'Service', could apply during mirror-resilvering of a disk, reload of a user permissions list, or other administrative work. win32WinSATTable.name: win32WinSATTable

ossatCPUScore.name: ossatCPUScore

ossatD3DScore.name: ossatD3DScore
ossatD3DScore.description: A score for the three-dimensional graphics (gaming) capabilities of the computer.

ossatDiskScore.name: ossatDiskScore
ossatDiskScore.description: A score for the sequential read throughput on the primary hard disk on the computer.

ossatGraphicsScore.name: ossatGraphicsScore

ossatMemoryScore.name: ossatMemoryScore
ossatMemoryScore.description: A score for the memory throughput and capacity of the computer.

ossatTimeTaken.name: ossatTimeTaken
ossatTimeTaken.description: This property must be set to 'MostRecentAssessment' in the WHERE clause of your WQL query.

ossatAssessmentState.description: State of the assessment. For a description of the possible values, see the WINSAT_ASSESSMENT_STATE enumeration.

ossatSPRLevel.name: ossatSPRLevel
ossatSPRLevel.description: Base score for the computer. For details on the score value, see http://msdn2.microsoft.com/en-us/library/aa969193.a spx

wmiProcesses.name: wmiProcesses
wmiProcesses.description: The Processes subcategory groups classes that represent system processes and threads.

win32ProcessTable.name: win32ProcessTable
win32ProcessTable.description: The Win32_Process WMI class represents a sequence of events on a Windows operating system. A descendent or member of this class is a sequence that consists of an interaction of one or more processors or interpreters, some executable code, and a set of inputs, for example, a client application running on a Windows system.

ospsIndex.name: ospsIndex
ospsIndex.description: The value of this object uniquely identifies the instance entry for this class.

ospsCaption.name: ospsCaption
ospsCaption.description: Short description of an object a one-line string.

ospsCommandLine.name: ospsCommandLine
ospsCommandLine.description: Command line used to start a specific process, if applicable. This property is new for Windows XP.

ospsCreationClassName.name: ospsCreationClassName
ospsCreationClassName.description: Name of the first concrete class in the inheritance chain that is used to create an instance. You can use this property with other key properties of the class to identify uniquely all instances of the class and its subclasses. This property is inherited from CIM_System

ospsCSCreationClassName.name: ospsCSCreationClassName
ospsCSCreationClassName.description: Creation class name of the scoping computer system.

ospsCSName.name: ospsCSName
ospsCSName.description: Name of the scoping computer system.

ospsExecutablePath.name: ospsExecutablePath
ospsExecutablePath.description: Path to the executable file of the process. Example: C:\WINDOWS\EXPLORER.EXE

ospsExecutionState.name: ospsExecutionState
ospsExecutionState.description: This property is not implemented and does not get populated for any instance of this class. This property is always NULL.

ospsHandleCount.name: ospsHandleCount
ospsHandleCount.description: Total number of open handles owned by the process. HandleCount is the sum of the handles currently open by each thread in this process. A handle is used to examine or modify the system resources. Each handle has an entry in a table that is maintained internally. Entries contain the addresses of the resources and data to identify the resource type.

ospsInstallDate.name: ospsInstallDate
ospsInstallDate.description: Date an object is installed. The object may be installed without a value being written to this property.

ospsKernelModeTime.name: ospsKernelModeTime
ospsKernelModeTime.description: Time in kernel mode, in 100 nanosecond units. If this information is not available, use a value of 0 (zero).

ospsMaximumWorkingSetSize.name: ospsMaximumWorkingSetSize
ospsMaximumWorkingSetSize.description: Maximum working set size of the process. The working set of a process is the set of memory pages visible to the process in physical RAM. These pages are resident, and available for an application to use without triggering a page fault. Example: 1413120

ospsMinimumWorkingSetSize.name: ospsMinimumWorkingSetSize
ospsMinimumWorkingSetSize.description: Minimum working set size of the process. The working set of a process is the set of memory pages visible to the process in physical RAM. These pages are resident and available for an application to use without triggering a page fault. Example: 20480

ospsName.name: ospsName
ospsName.description: Label for an object. When inherited by a subclass, the property can be overridden to be a key property.

ospsOSCreationClassName.name: ospsOSCreationClassName
ospsOSCreationClassName.description: Creation class name of the scoping operating system.

ospsOSName.name: ospsOSName
ospsOSName.description: Name of the scoping operating system.

ospsOtherOperationCount.name: ospsOtherOperationCount
ospsOtherOperationCount.description: Number of I/O operations performed that are not read or write operations.

ospsOtherTransferCount.name: ospsOtherTransferCount
ospsOtherTransferCount.description: Amount of data transferred during operations that are not read or write operations.

ospsPageFaults.name: ospsPageFaults
ospsPageFaults.description: Number of page faults that a process generates. Example: 10

ospsPageFileUsage.name: ospsPageFileUsage
ospsPageFileUsage.description: Amount of page file space that a process is using currently. Example: 102435

ospsParentProcessId.name: ospsParentProcessId
ospsParentProcessId.description: Unique identifier of the process that creates a process. Process identifier numbers are reused, so they only identify a process for the lifetime of that process. It is possible that the process identified by ParentProcessId is terminated, so ParentProcessId may not refer to a running process. It is also possible that ParentProcessId incorrectly refers to a process that reuses a process identifier. You can use the CreationDate property to determine whether the specified parent was created after the process represented by this Win32_Process instance was created.

ospsPeakPageFileUsage.name: ospsPeakPageFileUsage
ospsPeakPageFileUsage.description: Maximum amount of page file space used during the life of a process. Example: 102367

ospsPeakVirtualSize.name: ospsPeakVirtualSize
ospsPeakVirtualSize.description: Maximum virtual address space a process uses at any one time. Using virtual address space does not necessarily imply corresponding use of either disk or main memory pages. However, virtual space is finite, and by using too much the process might not be able to load libraries.

ospsPeakWorkingSetSize.name: ospsPeakWorkingSetSize
ospsPeakWorkingSetSize.description: Peak working set size of a process. Example: 1413120

ospsPriority.name: ospsPriority
ospsPriority.description: Scheduling priority of a process within an operating system. The higher the value, the higher priority a process receives. Priority values can range from 0 (zero), which is the lowest priority to 31, which is highest priority. Example: 7

ospsPrivatePageCount.name: ospsPrivatePageCount
ospsPrivatePageCount.description: Current number of pages allocated that are accessible only to the process represented by this Win32_Process instance.

ospsProcessId.name: ospsProcessId
ospsProcessId.description: Global process identifier that you can use to identify a process. The value is valid from the time a process is created until it is terminated.

ospsQuotaNonPagedPoolUsage.name: ospsQuotaNonPagedPoolUsage
ospsQuotaNonPagedPoolUsage.description: Quota amount of non-paged pool usage for a process. Example: 15

ospsQuotaPagedPoolUsage.name: ospsQuotaPagedPoolUsage
ospsQuotaPagedPoolUsage.description: Quota amount of paged pool usage for a process. Example: 22

ospsQuotaPeakNonPagedPoolUsage.name: ospsQuotaPeakNonPagedPoolUsage
ospsQuotaPeakNonPagedPoolUsage.description: Peak quota amount of non-paged pool usage for a process. Example: 31

ospsQuotaPeakPagedPoolUsage.name: ospsQuotaPeakPagedPoolUsage
ospsQuotaPeakPagedPoolUsage.description: Peak quota amount of paged pool usage for a process. Example: 31

ospsSessionId.name: ospsSessionId
ospsSessionId.description: Unique identifier that an operating system generates when a session is created. A session spans a period of time from log on until log off from a specific system.

ospsStatus.name: ospsStatus
ospsStatus.description: This property is not implemented and does not get populated for any instance of this class. It is always NULL.

ospsTerminationDate.name: ospsTerminationDate
ospsTerminationDate.description: Process was stopped or terminated. To get the termination time, a handle to the process must be held open. Otherwise, this property returns NULL.

ospsThreadCount.name: ospsThreadCount
ospsThreadCount.description: Number of active threads in a process. An instruction is the basic unit of execution in a processor, and a thread is the object that executes an instruction. Each running process has at least one thread. This property is for computers running Windows NT only.

ospsUserModeTime.name: ospsUserModeTime
ospsUserModeTime.description: Time in user mode, in 100 nanosecond units. If this information is not available, use a value of 0 (zero).

ospsVirtualSize.name: ospsVirtualSize
ospsVirtualSize.description: Current size of the virtual address space that a process is using. Using virtual address space does not necessarily imply corresponding use of either disk or main memory pages. Virtual space is finite, and by using too much, the process might not be able to load libraries.

ospsWindowsVersion.name: ospsWindowsVersion
ospsWindowsVersion.description: Version of Windows in which the process is running. Example: 4.0

ospsWorkingSetSize.name: ospsWorkingSetSize
ospsWorkingSetSize.description: Amount of memory in bytes that a process needs to execute efficiently for an operating system that uses page-based memory management. If the system does not have enough memory (less than the working set size), thrashing occurs. If the size of the working set is not known, use NULL or 0 (zero). If working set data is provided, you can monitor the information to understand the changing memory requirements of a process.

win32ThreadTable.name: win32ThreadTable
win32ThreadTable.description: The Win32_Thread WMI class represents a thread of execution. While a process must have one thread of execution, the process can create other threads to execute tasks in parallel. Threads share the process environment, thus multiple threads under the same process use less memory than the same number of processes.

ostdIndex.name: ostdIndex
ostdIndex.description: The value of this object uniquely identifies the instance entry for this class.

ostdCaption.name: ostdCaption
ostdCaption.description: Short description (one-line string) of the object.

ostdCreationClassName.name: ostdCreationClassName
ostdCreationClassName.description: Name of the first concrete class to appear in the inheritance chain used in the creation of an instance. When used with the other key properties of the class, the property allows all instances of this class and its subclasses to be uniquely identified.

ostdCSCreationClassName.name: ostdCSCreationClassName
ostdCSCreationClassName.description: Creation class name of the scoping computer system.

ostdCSName.name: ostdCSName
ostdCSName.description: Name of the scoping computer system.

ostdElapsedTime.name: ostdElapsedTime
ostdElapsedTime.description: Total execution time given to this thread since its creation.

ostdExecutionState.name: ostdExecutionState
ostdExecutionState.description: Current operating condition of the thread.

ostdHandle.name: ostdHandle
ostdHandle.description: Handle to a thread. The handle has full access rights by default. With the correct security access, the handle can be used in any function that accepts a thread handle. Depending on the inheritance flag specified when it is created, this handle can be inherited by child processes.

ostdInstallDate.name: ostdInstallDate
ostdInstallDate.description: Object was installed. This property does not need a value to indicate that the object is installed.

ostdKernelModeTime.name: ostdKernelModeTime
ostdKernelModeTime.description: Time in kernel mode, in 100 nanoseconds. If this information is not available, a value of 0 should be used.

ostdName.name: ostdName
ostdName.description: Label by which the object is known. When subclassed, the property can be overridden to be a key property.

ostdOSCreationClassName.name: ostdOSCreationClassName
ostdOSCreationClassName.description: Creation class name of the scoping operating system.

ostdOSName.name: ostdOSName
ostdOSName.description: Name of the scoping operating system.

ostdPriority.name: ostdPriority
ostdPriority.description: Dynamic priority of the thread. Each thread has a dynamic priority that the scheduler uses to determine which thread to execute. Initially, a thread's dynamic priority is the same as its base priority. The system can raise and lower the dynamic priority, to ensure that it is responsive (guaranteeing that no threads are starved for processor time). The system does not boost the priority of threads with a base priority level between 16 and 31. Only threads with a base priority between 0 and 15 receive dynamic priority boosts. Higher numbers indicate higher priorities.

ostdPriorityBase.name: ostdPriorityBase
ostdPriorityBase.description: Current base priority of a thread. The operating system may raise the thread's dynamic priority above the base priority if the thread is handling user input, or lower it toward the base priority if the thread becomes compute-bound. The PriorityBase property can have a value between 0 and 31.

ostdProcessCreationClassName.name: ostdProcessCreationClassName
ostdProcessCreationClassName.description: Value of the scoping process CreationClassName property.

ostdProcessHandle.name: ostdProcessHandle
ostdProcessHandle.description: Process that created the thread. The contents of this property can be used by Windows API elements.

ostdStartAddress.name: ostdStartAddress
ostdStartAddress.description: Starting address of the thread. Because any application with appropriate access to the thread can change the thread's context, this value may only be an approximation of the thread's starting address.

ostdStatus.name: ostdStatus
ostdStatus.description: Current status of the object. Various operational and non-operational statuses can be defined. Operational statuses include: 'OK', 'Degraded', and 'Pred Fail' (an element, such as a SMART-enabled hard drive, may be functioning properly but predicting a failure in the near future). Non-operational statuses include: 'Error', 'Starting', 'Stopping', and 'Service'. The latter, 'Service', could apply during mirror-resilvering of a disk, reload of a user permissions list, or other administrative work. Not all such work is on-line, yet the managed element is neither 'OK' nor in one of the other states.

ostdThreadState.name: ostdThreadState
ostdThreadState.description: Current execution state for the thread.

ostdThreadWaitReason.name: ostdThreadWaitReason
ostdThreadWaitReason.description: Reason why the thread is waiting. The value is only valid if the ThreadState member is set to Waiting (6). Event pairs allow communication with protected subsystems .

ostdUserModeTime.name: ostdUserModeTime
ostdUserModeTime.description: Time in user mode, in 100 nanoseconds. If this information is not available, a value of 0 should be used.

win32CreateProcess.name: win32CreateProcess
win32CreateProcess.description: This OID can only be written to and cannot be read! Creates a new process. For security reasons, the script/program to be executed must reside in 'spawn' directory under the SNMP Informant-OS installation.

wmiSchedulerJobs.name: wmiSchedulerJobs
wmiSchedulerJobs.description: The Scheduler Jobs subcategory groups classes that represent scheduled job settings.

win32CurrentTimeTable.name: win32CurrentTimeTable
win32CurrentTimeTable.description: The Win32_CurrentTime abstract is a singleton WMI class that describes a point in time by using the component items such as milliseconds, seconds, minutes, hours, days, days of the week, week in the month, months, quarters, and years.

osctQuarter.name: osctQuarter

osctSecond.name: osctSecond

osctWeekInMonth.name: osctWeekInMonth
osctWeekInMonth.description: Current week (1-6) in the current month (1-12).

osctYear.name: osctYear
osctYear.description: Current year that matches the query (4 digits).

win32ScheduledJobTable.name: win32ScheduledJobTable
win32ScheduledJobTable.description: The Win32_ScheduledJob WMI class represents a job created with the AT command in a command window from Start, Run, or from Control Panel, Scheduled Jobs. You can enumerate or delete any existing jobs that are displayed in the Control Panel, Scheduled Jobs dialog box by using the Win32_ScheduledJob instances. This class is only instrumented on Windows NT 4.0 and later. Each job scheduled against the schedule service is stored persistently (the scheduler can start a job after a reboot), and is executed at the specified time and day of the week or month. If the computer is not active or if the scheduled service is not running at the specified job time, the schedule service runs the specified job on the next day at the specified time. Jobs are scheduled according to Universal Coordinated Time (UTC) with bias offset from Greenwich mean time (GMT), which means that a job can be specified using any time zone. The Win32_ScheduledJob class returns the local time with UTC offset when enumerating an object, and converts to local time when creating new jobs. For example, a job specified to run on a computer in Boston at 10:30 P.M. Monday PST time will be scheduled to run locally at 1:30 A.M. Tuesday EST. Note that a client must take into account whether or not daylight savings time is in operation on the local computer, and if it is, then subtract a bias of 60 minutes from the UTC offset.

ossjIndex.name: ossjIndex
ossjIndex.description: The value of this object uniquely identifies the instance entry for this class.

ossjCommand.description: Name of the command, batch program, or binary file (and command line arguments) that the schedule service uses to invoke the job. Example: 'defrag /q /f'

ossjDaysOfMonth.description: Days of the month when the job is scheduled to run. If a job is scheduled to run on multiple days of the month, these values can be joined in a logical OR. ossjDaysOfWeek.name: ossjDaysOfWeek
ossjDaysOfWeek.description: Days of the week when a job is scheduled to run. If a job is scheduled to run on multiple days of the week, the values can be joined in a logical OR. For example, if a job is scheduled to run on Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays the value of the DaysOfWeek property would be 1 OR 4 OR 16. ossjElapsedTime.name: ossjElapsedTime
ossjElapsedTime.description: Length of time that the job has been executing.

ossjInstallDate.name: ossjInstallDate
ossjInstallDate.description: Object was installed. This property does not need a value to indicate that the object is installed.

ossjInteractWithDesktop.name: ossjInteractWithDesktop
ossjInteractWithDesktop.description: Specified job is interactive, which means that a user can give input to a scheduled job while it is executing.

ossjJobId.name: ossjJobId
ossjJobId.description: Identifying number of the job. It is used by methods as a handle to one job being scheduled on this computer.

ossjJobStatus.name: ossjJobStatus
ossjJobStatus.description: Status of execution the last time this job was scheduled to run.

ossjName.name: ossjName
ossjName.description: Label by which the object is known. When subclassed, the property can be overridden to be a key property.

ossjNotify.name: ossjNotify
ossjNotify.description: User to be notified when job completes or fails.

ossjPriority.name: ossjPriority
ossjPriority.description: Urgency or importance of execution of a job.

ossjRunRepeatedly.name: ossjRunRepeatedly
ossjRunRepeatedly.description: Scheduled job runs repeatedly on the days that the job is scheduled. If FALSE, then the job is run one time.

ossjStartTime.name: ossjStartTime
ossjStartTime.description: UTC time to run the job, in the form of YYYYMMDDHHMMSS.MMMMMM(+-)OOO, where YYYYMMDD must be replaced by ********. The replacement is necessary because the scheduling service only allows jobs to be configured to run one time, or run on a day of the month or week. A job cannot be run on a specific date. Example: ********123000.000000-420 implies 12:30 P.M. PST with daylight savings time in effect.

ossjStatus.name: ossjStatus
ossjStatus.description: Current status of the object. Various operational and non-operational statuses can be defined. Operational statuses include: 'OK', 'Degraded', and 'Pred Fail' (an element, such as a SMART-enabled hard drive, may be functioning properly but predicting a failure in the near future). Non-operational statuses include: 'Error', 'Starting', 'Stopping', and 'Service'. The latter, 'Service', could apply during mirror-resilvering of a disk, reload of a user permissions list, or other administrative work. Not all such work is on-line, yet the managed element is neither 'OK' nor in one of the other states.

ossjUntilTime.name: ossjUntilTime
ossjUntilTime.description: Time after which the job is invalid or must be stopped.

wmiServices.name: wmiServices
wmiServices.description: The Services subcategory groups classes that represent services and base services.

win32ServiceTable.name: win32ServiceTable
win32ServiceTable.description: The Win32_Service WMI class represents a service on a Windows computer system. A service application conforms to the interface rules of the Service Control Manager (SCM), and can be started by a user automatically at system boot through the Services control panel utility, or by an application that uses the service functions included in the Windows API. Services can execute when no user is logged on to the system.

ossvcIndex.name: ossvcIndex
ossvcIndex.description: The value of this object uniquely identifies the instance entry for this class.

ossvcCaption.name: ossvcCaption
ossvcCaption.description: Short description of the object a one-line string.

ossvcCheckPoint.name: ossvcCheckPoint
ossvcCheckPoint.description: Value that the service increments periodically to report its progress during a long start, stop, pause, or continue operation. For example, the service increments this value as it completes each step of its initialization when it is starting up. The user interface program that invokes the operation on the service uses this value to track the progress of the service during a lengthy operation. This value is not valid and should be zero when the service does not have a start, stop, pause, or continue operation pending.

ossvcCreationClassName.name: ossvcCreationClassName
ossvcCreationClassName.description: Name of the first concrete class to appear in the inheritance chain used in the creation of an instance. When used with the other key properties of the class, the property allows all instances of this class and its subclasses to be uniquely identified.

ossvcDesktopInteract.name: ossvcDesktopInteract
ossvcDesktopInteract.description: Service can create or communicate with windows on the desktop.

ossvcDisplayName.name: ossvcDisplayName
ossvcDisplayName.description: Display name of the service. This string has a maximum length of 256 characters. The name is case-preserved in the Service Control Manager. However, DisplayName comparisons are always case-insensitive. Constraint: accepts the same value as the Name property. Example: 'Atdisk'

ossvcErrorControl.name: ossvcErrorControl
ossvcErrorControl.description: Severity of the error if this service fails to start during startup. The value indicates the action taken by the startup program if failure occurs. All errors are logged by the computer system. Value Meaning 'Ignore' User is not notified. 'Normal' User is notified. 'Severe' System is restarted with the last-known-good configuration. 'Critical' System attempts to restart with a good configuration. 'Unknown' Severity of the error is unknown.

ossvcExitCode.name: ossvcExitCode
ossvcExitCode.description: Windows error code defining any problems encountered in starting or stopping the service. This property is set to ERROR_SERVICE_SPECIFIC_ERROR (1066) when the error is unique to the service represented by this class, and information about the error is available in the ServiceSpecificExitCode property. The service sets this value to NO_ERROR when running, and again upon normal termination.

ossvcInstallDate.name: ossvcInstallDate
ossvcInstallDate.description: Date object is installed. This property does not need a value to indicate that the object is installed.

ossvcName.name: ossvcName
ossvcName.description: Unique identifier of the service that provides an indication of the functionality that is managed. This functionality is described in more detail in the Description property of the object.

ossvcPathName.name: ossvcPathName
ossvcPathName.description: Fully-qualified path to the service binary file that implements the service. Example: '\SystemRoot\System32\drivers\afd.sys'

ossvcProcessId.name: ossvcProcessId
ossvcProcessId.description: Process identifier of the service. Example: 324

ossvcServiceSpecificExitCode.name: ossvcServiceSpecificExitCode
ossvcServiceSpecificExitCode.description: Service-specific error code for errors that occur while the service is either starting or stopping. The exit codes are defined by the service represented by this class. This value is only set when the ExitCode property value is ERROR_SERVICE_SPECIFIC_ERROR (1066).

ossvcServiceType.name: ossvcServiceType
ossvcServiceType.description: Type of service provided to calling processes.

ossvcStartMode.name: ossvcStartMode
ossvcStartMode.description: Start mode of the Windows base service. Value Meaning 'Boot' Device driver started by the operating system loader (valid only for driver services) 'System' Device driver started by the IoInitSystem method (valid only for driver services) 'Auto' Service to be started automatically by the service control manager during system startup 'Manual' Service to be started by the service control manager when a process calls the StartService method 'Disabled' Service that cannot be started

ossvcStartName.name: ossvcStartName
ossvcStartName.description: Account name under which a service runs. Depending on the service type, the account name may be in the form of DomainName\Username. The service process is logged by using one of these two forms when it runs. If the account belongs to the built-in domain, then .\Username can be specified. For kernel or system level drivers, StartName contains the driver object name (that is, \FileSystem\Rdr or \Driver\Xns) which the input and output (I/O) system uses to load the device driver. Additionally, if NULL is specified, the driver runs with a default object name created by the I/O system based on the service name. Example: 'DWDOM\Admin' Windows XP: You may use UPN format (Username@DomainName) to specify the StartName. Windows 2000: To change from a specified user to the LocalSystem account, use .\LocalSystem.

ossvcState.name: ossvcState
ossvcState.description: Current state of the base service. Setting the state to stopped, running, or paused will either stop, start (or resume), or pause the service.

ossvcStatus.description: Current status of the object. Various operational and non-operational statuses can be defined. Operational statuses include: 'OK', 'Degraded', and 'Pred Fail' (an element, such as a SMART-enabled hard drive, may be functioning properly but predicting a failure in the near future). Non-operational statuses include: 'Error', 'Starting', 'Stopping', and 'Service'. The latter, 'Service', could apply during mirror-resilvering of a disk, reload of a user permissions list, or other administrative work. ossvcSystemName.name: ossvcSystemName

ossvcTagId.name: ossvcTagId
ossvcTagId.description: Unique tag value for this service in the group. A value of 0 (zero) indicates that the service does not have a tag. A tag can be used to order service startup within a load order group by specifying a tag order vector in the registry located at: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Control \GroupOrderList. ossvcWaitHint.name: ossvcWaitHint

win32DFSNodeTable.name: win32DFSNodeTable
win32DFSNodeTable.description: The Win32_DFSNode WMI class represents a root or junction node of a domain-based or stand-alone distributed file system (DFS). The DFS root is also represented by this class because the root is also a node. Each link has one or more targets or actual share paths for the storage defined by the Win32_DFSTarget class. This class is new for Windows Server 2003.

osdfsnCaption.name: osdfsnCaption

osdfsnInstallDate.name: osdfsnInstallDate

osdfsnName.description: Identifier for the DFS node. It is the same as the entry path of a node, based on the Universal Naming Convention (UNC). ShareName is the name of the share published on the host server. PathToLink is the path to the physical share. DomainName is the name of the domain that hosts the DFS root volume. FtDfsName is the name of the fault-tolerant DFS root published. PathToLink is the path to the physical share. This property overrides the Name property in CIM_ManagedSystemElement.

osdfsnRoot.name: osdfsnRoot
osdfsnRoot.description: Indicate whether the node is a DFS root or a link. A value of TRUE indicates that the node is a root.

osdfsnTimeout.name: osdfsnTimeout

win32ShareTable.name: win32ShareTable
win32ShareTable.description: The Win32_Share class represents a shared resource on a Windows system. This may be a disk drive, printer, inter-process communication, or other shareable device. For information on retrieving WMI classes see Retrieving a Class.

osshIndex.name: osshIndex
osshIndex.description: The value of this object uniquely identifies the instance entry for this class.

osshAccessMask.description: List of access rights to the given file or directory held by the user or group on whose behalf the instance is returned. osshAllowMaximum.name: osshAllowMaximum

win32ShadowContextTable.name: win32ShadowContextTable
win32ShadowContextTable.description: The Win32_ShadowContext class specifies how a shadow copy is to be created, queried, or deleted, and the degree of writer involvement. Windows XP and earlier: This class is not available.

osscxIndex.name: osscxIndex
osscxIndex.description: The value of this object uniquely identifies the instance entry for this class.

osscxClientAccessible.name: osscxClientAccessible
osscxClientAccessible.description: If true, the shadow copy is created by the Windows Previous Versions component.

osscxDifferential.name: osscxDifferential
osscxDifferential.description: If true, the shadow copy is created by a differential shadow copy provider. The provider can be implemented in hardware or software.

osscxExposedLocally.name: osscxExposedLocally
osscxExposedLocally.description: If true, the shadow copy is exposed on a remote computer with a network share. If both ExposedLocally and ExposedRemotely are false, the shadow copy is hidden.

osscxExposedRemotely.name: osscxExposedRemotely
osscxExposedRemotely.description: If true, the shadow copy is exposed on a remote computer with a network share. If both ExposedRemotely and ExposedLocally are false, the shadow copy is hidden.

osscxHardwareAssisted.name: osscxHardwareAssisted

osscxImported.name: osscxImported
osscxImported.description: If true, the shadow copy is imported to a computer by using the Import method not created by using the Create method.

osscxNoAutoRelease.name: osscxNoAutoRelease

osscxNotSurfaced.name: osscxNotSurfaced

osscxNoWriters.name: osscxNoWriters

osscxPersistent.name: osscxPersistent

osscxPlex.name: osscxPlex

osscxTransportable.name: osscxTransportable
osscxTransportable.description: If true, the shadow copy can be surfaced on another computer. If false, and the volumes are surfaced locally, it may not be possible to surface them later on a different computer.

win32ShadowCopyTable.name: win32ShadowCopyTable
win32ShadowCopyTable.description: The Win32_ShadowCopy class is a storage extent that represents a duplicate copy of the original volume at a previous time. Windows XP and earlier: This class is not available.

osscpExposedName.description: File system name of a shadow copy when it is exposed. The ExposedName property might contain a drive letter or mount point. The ExposedName property is NULL when a shadow copy is hidden or otherwise not exposed.

osscpExposedRemotely.name: osscpExposedRemotely

osscpHardwareAssisted.name: osscpHardwareAssisted
osscpHardwareAssisted.description: If true, the shadow copy is created by a hardware shadow copy provider.

osscpID.name: osscpID

osscpImported.name: osscpImported
osscpImported.description: If true, the shadow copy is imported to a computer by using the Import method not created by using the Create method.

osscpNoAutoRelease.name: osscpNoAutoRelease
osscpNoAutoRelease.description: If true, the shadow copy is retained after the requestor process ends. If false, the shadow copy is automatically deleted when the requestor process ends.

oselfCaption.name: oselfCaption
oselfCaption.description: Short description (one-line string) of the object.

oselfCompressed.name: oselfCompressed
oselfCompressed.description: If True, a file of Windows NT events is compressed.

oselfCompressionMethod.name: oselfCompressionMethod
oselfCompressionMethod.description: Algorithm or tool used to compress the logical file of Windows NT events. If it is not possible (or not desired) to describe the compression scheme (perhaps because it is not known), use the following words: 'Unknown' to represent that it is not known whether the logical file is compressed. 'Compressed' to represent that the file is compressed but either its compression scheme is not known or not disclosed. 'Not Compressed' to represent that the logical file is not compressed.

oselfCreationClassName.description: Name of the first concrete class to appear in the inheritance chain used in the creation of an instance. When used with the other key properties of the class, the property allows all instances of this class and its subclasses to be uniquely identified.

oselfCreationDate.name: oselfCreationDate
oselfCreationDate.description: File of Windows NT events was created.

oselfDrive.name: oselfDrive
oselfDrive.description: Drive letter (including colon) of the file of Windows NT events. Example: 'c:'

oselfEightDotThreeFileName.name: oselfEightDotThreeFileName
oselfEightDotThreeFileName.description: DOS-compatible file name for this file of Windows NT events. Example: 'c:\progra~1'

oselfFileName.name: oselfFileName
oselfFileName.description: File name (without extension) of the file of Windows NT events. Example: 'autoexec'

oselfFileSize.name: oselfFileSize
oselfFileSize.description: Size of the file of Windows NT events (in bytes).

oselfFileType.name: oselfFileType

oselfHidden.name: oselfHidden
oselfHidden.description: If True, a file of Windows NT events is hidden.

oselfInstallDate.name: oselfInstallDate
oselfInstallDate.description: Object is installed. This property does not need a value to indicate that the object is installed.

oselfInUseCount.name: oselfInUseCount
oselfInUseCount.description: Number of 'file opens' that are currently active against the file of Windows NT events.

oselfLastAccessed.name: oselfLastAccessed
oselfLastAccessed.description: File of Windows NT events was last accessed.

oselfLastModified.name: oselfLastModified
oselfLastModified.description: File of Windows NT events was last modified.

oselfLogFileName.name: oselfLogFileName
oselfLogFileName.description: Name of the file of Windows NT events. Standard log file names include Application, System, and Security.

oselfManufacturer.name: oselfManufacturer
oselfManufacturer.description: Manufacturer from version resource, if one is present.

oselfName.name: oselfName
oselfName.description: Inherited name that serves as a key of a logical file instance of Windows NT events within a file system. Full path names should be provided. Example: 'c:\winnt\system\win.ini'

oselfNumberOfRecords.name: oselfNumberOfRecords
oselfNumberOfRecords.description: Number of records in the file of Windows NT events. This value is determined by calling the Windows function GetNumberOfEventLogRecords.

oselfOverwriteOutDated.name: oselfOverwriteOutDated
oselfOverwriteOutDated.description: Number of days after which an event can be overwritten. Value Meaning 0: Any entry can be overwritten when necessary. 1..365: Events that have been in the log file for one year (365 days) or less can be overwritten. 4294967295: Nothing can be ever be overwritten.

oselfOverWritePolicy.name: oselfOverWritePolicy
oselfOverWritePolicy.description: Current overwrite policy the Event Log service employs for this log file. Data can be never overwritten, or overwritten when necessary or when outdated. 'Never' The value of OverwriteOutDated equals 4294967295.

oselfPath.name: oselfPath
oselfPath.description: Path of the file of Windows NT event. This includes leading and trailing backslashes. Example: '\windows\system\'

oselfReadable.name: oselfReadable
oselfReadable.description: If True, a file of Windows NT event can be read.

oselfSources.name: oselfSources

oselfStatus.name: oselfStatus
oselfStatus.description: Current status of the object. Various operational and non-operational statuses can be defined.
